description: Unusual song-type for species (as far as I know), first part is typical BTNW, second part is somewhat reminiscent of a Cerulean Warbler. In the recording, there are at least three counter-singing individuals, maybe four but did not keep notes at the time. This is the only location in the Bankhead National Forest Sipsey Wilderness Area I've heard this song type. First noticed it at this location in May of 2013. Interestingly a Cerulean Warbler was found singing and photographed at this location 2013-05-09. However I wonder if subsequent reports to eBird of Cerulean Warbler at this location may have been these atypical BTNWs. Both times I've visited this site in 2013 and 2014 I've never had CERW but have had visual of BTNWs singing this song type.
remarks: Unusual song-type for species (as far as I know), first part is typical BTNW, second part is somewhat reminiscent of a Cerulean Warbler.
